<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO ED</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep  6 12:36:18 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ed,<br><br>
To label Cook as volatile and intense is rather an understatement.<br><br>
He has talked of the guilt, shame, and silence of returning veterans. The hippies of the counterculture never made me ashamed. I never looked at them as owing me anything, either.<br><br>
There were those who told us it was our duty to serve our country. Which many of us did. However when we returned many who told us &quot;go&quot; were not willing to engage us in dialogue. I am sure that there are many varying reasons. Maybe some were just plain uncomfortable talking about it.<br><br>
More than one time the very people who said that Vietnam was a good idea, changed their tune by saying, &quot;We should never have gone there in the first place.&quot; A great way to cop out, and an effective way to absolve oneself of the blame for a war which provided a very bad taste. We were left holding the bag.<br><br>
If you were to ask me my opinion of Mr Cook Barela, I would say that he is a very proud man. A good man. A man who as a US Marine and a law enforcement officer has been crapped on many times.<br><br>
Now the one thing that Cook Barela doesn't realize is that the ones who hold him in the highest regard are the ones who disagree with him and don't mind letting him know.<br><br>
Think about those who really turned their backs on us. The ones who sent us and then had nothing to do with us when we returned.<br><br>
Am I bitter? Not anymore. But I can damn sure guarantee you that what I went through and saw is going to be said.<br><br>
Cook, I realize that these are only words on a screen, but allow me to say that you have real friends here.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


